column2: Stephen Stocking
column25: Florida Museum of Natural History Herpetology Collection
column69: Miami, SE corner of NW 71st St and NW 35th Ave
column153: 2 juveniles and 1 adult Ctenosaura sp. (probably C. similis based on other locality records on EDD Maps) at 10:30 AM at the corner of NW 71st St and NW 35th Ave. Juvenile caught on SE side of intersection, utilizing hole in warehouse wall for refuge. 1 other juvenile, and 1 adult observed on SW side of intersection inside a chain-link fenced area. Site is 1 block east of railroad lines, they could serve as a corridor for lizards to disperse from existing populations to the north (Amelia Earhart Park). Caught 1 juvenile with a fishing line and crickets for bait. Photos attached. I am hoping someone can verify the species, C. similis or C. pectinata from the photos attached. Unfortunately I did not obtain any site or in-situ photos; I will attempt to return to site when my schedule permits. Specimen is available for voucher.

column153: I saw a large lizard while riding on the bike path. It was quite fast and stopped on top of the rocks near the bike trail. I stopped and stared at it for a minute trying to note any characteristics. It was about 24 inches or more in length. Slim body with a smooth small head like a snake. It was brownish rocky color with 3 wide light faded green stripes between the front and rear legs on the sides of the belly. Long sharp tail. I don't remember any spines or crest on the head. I can't find any pics of exactly what I saw
